Psychedelic clinical trials are expanding at a pace that would have been difficult to imagine a decade ago. Researchers are now studying psilocybin, MDMA, LSD, DMT, ketamine, and newer psychedelic compounds for depression, PTSD, addiction, chronic illness, and neurological conditions. Some of the most important studies are expected to reach major milestones during 2026 and 2027. These are the psychedelic clinical trials most likely to influence the future of mental health treatment.

## The Psychedelic Clinical Trials That Could Change Everything

The past three years have brought a significant increase in psychedelic research. This growth has been supported by [regulatory changes](https://thepsychedelicdigest.com/blog/psychedelic-therapy-australia-2026), major private investment, and increasing demand for mental health treatments that work differently from conventional antidepressants.

More than 100 psychedelic clinical trials are reportedly active worldwide as of July 2026. They cover conditions ranging from treatment-resistant depression and PTSD to alcohol use disorder and neurodegenerative disease.

Not every trial will produce a positive result. However, several major studies could determine whether psychedelic-assisted therapies move closer to mainstream clinical use.

## Psilocybin for Treatment-Resistant Depression

PSILODEP-2 is a phase 2 randomised controlled trial led by Monash University. The study is investigating psilocybin-assisted therapy for people with treatment-resistant depression.

With 160 participants across multiple locations, it is one of the largest psilocybin trials conducted in the Southern Hemisphere.

Treatment-resistant depression describes depression that has not improved after multiple standard treatments. People in this group often have limited options beyond trying additional medications, psychotherapy, brain stimulation, or combinations of these approaches.

The study is expected to complete in November 2026, with initial results potentially becoming available in early 2027. Positive findings could strengthen the evidence for psilocybin-assisted therapy as an alternative for people who have not benefited from conventional antidepressants.

## MDMA-Assisted Therapy for PTSD

MDMA-assisted therapy remains one of the most closely watched areas of psychedelic medicine. Researchers have been studying whether MDMA can help people engage with traumatic memories while experiencing reduced fear and emotional defensiveness.

Earlier phase 3 research reported that a significant proportion of participants no longer met the diagnostic criteria for PTSD after completing treatment. These findings generated widespread interest, but regulators have continued to examine questions involving study design, therapist conduct, safety monitoring, and how the treatment would be delivered outside clinical trials.

Confirmatory research will be essential for determining whether MDMA-assisted therapy can eventually become an approved treatment for PTSD.

The key questions are no longer limited to whether MDMA can reduce symptoms. Researchers and regulators must also establish:

* How therapists should be trained
* How treatment sessions should be supervised
* Which patients are appropriate candidates
* How adverse effects should be recorded
* How clinics can prevent misconduct
* Whether the benefits remain after treatment ends

The future of MDMA-assisted therapy will depend on both clinical efficacy and the safety of the treatment model surrounding the medicine.

## LSD for Alcohol Use Disorder

LSD is also returning to clinical research after decades of restrictions. One of the most important areas under investigation is alcohol use disorder.

MindMed has studied LSD-based treatment for people experiencing problematic alcohol use. The trial involves approximately 200 participants across several research sites, making it one of the largest modern LSD studies.

Alcohol use disorder can be difficult to treat because it involves biological dependence, emotional patterns, social conditions, and deeply established behaviours. Existing medications can help some people, but they are not effective for everyone and adherence can be difficult.

Researchers are examining whether a psychedelic experience, combined with psychological support, can help people interrupt repetitive patterns and develop a different relationship with alcohol.

The results will be important for the broader addiction field. A positive trial could encourage further studies involving nicotine dependence, opioid use disorder, stimulant addiction, and behavioural addictions.

## Psilocybin and Neurodegenerative Disease

One of the most experimental areas of psychedelic research involves neurodegenerative conditions such as Alzheimer's disease.

Most current psychedelic studies focus on the psychological distress associated with serious illness rather than reversing the illness itself. Psilocybin has already been investigated for depression and anxiety in people facing cancer and other life-threatening diagnoses.

Researchers are now becoming interested in whether psychedelic-related mechanisms could also influence neuroplasticity, inflammation, cognition, or emotional functioning in neurodegenerative disease.

Preclinical research suggests that some psychedelics may promote structural plasticity and influence inflammatory signalling. However, these findings do not prove that psilocybin can prevent or reverse cognitive decline in humans.

Early clinical studies will need to separate several possible effects:

* Reduced depression following diagnosis
* Reduced fear and existential distress
* Improved quality of life
* Changes in cognitive flexibility
* Changes in inflammatory markers
* Direct effects on disease progression

The emotional benefits may prove meaningful even if psychedelics do not alter the underlying neurological disease.

## DMT and Short-Acting Psychedelic Treatments

DMT is attracting interest partly because of its short duration. A traditional psilocybin session may last six hours or longer, while some forms of DMT can produce a much shorter psychedelic experience.

This matters commercially and clinically. Long treatment sessions require specialised rooms, several hours of professional supervision, and significant staffing costs.

A shorter psychedelic treatment could potentially make therapy easier to deliver. However, a shorter experience does not automatically mean a safer or more effective one.

Researchers are studying whether DMT and related compounds could produce rapid benefits for depression while reducing the time patients need to spend in a clinic. Other companies are developing modified psychedelic molecules designed to preserve therapeutic effects while shortening or removing the hallucinogenic experience.

This research could lead to several different treatment models rather than one standard form of psychedelic therapy.

## Ketamine Research and Rapid-Acting Antidepressants

Ketamine is not a classic serotonergic psychedelic, but it remains central to the psychedelic medicine conversation because of its rapid antidepressant effects.

Unlike psilocybin and LSD, ketamine already has a long history of medical use as an anaesthetic. Ketamine clinics now operate in several countries, and esketamine has received regulatory approval for certain forms of treatment-resistant depression.

Researchers continue to investigate:

* The ideal number of ketamine sessions
* How long antidepressant effects last
* Whether psychotherapy improves outcomes
* Which patients are most likely to respond
* The risks of repeated or long-term use
* How ketamine compares with psilocybin-assisted therapy

Ketamine may also offer clues about how rapid changes in neuroplasticity can affect depression. Understanding these mechanisms could support the development of entirely new psychiatric medicines.

## Why Australia Has Become a Psychedelic Research Hub

Australia has become an important location for psychedelic research due to its clinical trial infrastructure, university research programmes, private investment, and changing regulatory environment.

Since July 2023, authorised psychiatrists have been able to prescribe psilocybin for treatment-resistant depression and MDMA for PTSD under tightly controlled conditions. This policy made Australia the first country to create a national medical prescribing pathway for these substances.

The change did not make psychedelic therapy broadly available. Treatment remains expensive, highly restricted, and limited to approved practitioners and eligible patients.

However, the regulatory decision increased international attention on Australia's psychedelic sector. Universities, clinics, charities, and biotechnology companies are now involved in studies covering psilocybin, MDMA, DMT, and related compounds.

